The Prague Stock Exchange finished with fewer points at the end of the day
After the morning's rapid fall, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
The transactions in ČEZ shares reached approximately half their value on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, early on Tuesday, reacted immediately to Monday's fall as it fell about 6%.
The decline this time is due to the fall in stock prices on Wall Street.
Here too the market reaction to the result of the vote in the US House of Representatives that refused to support the financial secretary's stabilization plan is expressed.
The fall in stocks in Asia
Asian stock markets fell dramatically on Tuesday, though the index eventually eased some of the losses.
The Hang Seng Stock Exchange in Hong Kong was down nearly 4 percent during the day, but later eased its losses by cutting the decline by almost 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index that tracks movements in Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange fell 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent but in the end, the losses dropped to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange according to the Index Secretary fell 3.6 percent.
"The rescue actions scheduled in the US are insecure and this influences the financial market around the world", said Hong Kong's Chief Currency Officer Joseph Yam.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it alone determines its monetary policy, i.e. it is independent of the Central Bank of China.
Hong Kong's interest rates are on par with those in the United States.
American lawmakers should reconvene as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and pass a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens to make the falls felt in other countries.
Bloodbath of American stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected a financial bailout plan that would have cost $700 billion.
The lawmakers, in that way, ignored President George Bush's invitation to support his plan.
For Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
