Armed struggle: the MP3 player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile phone plays MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
Which seems clear to me that it's better to buy only the phone.
Still, there are enough reasons for man to acquire only the reproductive organ.
The choice depends largely on the way it is used and the requirements of the future owner.
It will probably be difficult for me to get the most modern turntables to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album on.
Moreover, this type of music products such as LP records are no longer being sold, and as far as their quality is concerned there is not a single objective reason to continue buying them.
If you have a lot of vinyl records of art rock, jazz, and blues on your shelves, you are probably dreaming of at least one of these.
This is the same with music that's coming, which is compressed music, simplified music -- music in MP3.
And here there are categories of price and quality.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, as it is for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly try the 20 crown market helmets.
Two extremes, between which there's enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
It also determines battery life.
Some of the best players do much more than just play music and even that which even most cell phones cannot.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to basic functions like calling, texting, it can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera and even navigate.
And when you take into consideration the smartphone and the PDA, you're going to have a small computer in your pocket, too.
This is a small miracle since no fridge can make a grill and no television can take pictures.
The universality of mobile phones also brings us disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your phone, the earlier the indicator on the screen lights up asking to be recharged.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy drains.
Few cell phones can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simpler ones) clearly have a higher performance.
So keep in mind that cheap phones won't play for more than two hours.
If, on top of this, they constantly call get still, for more safety, a charger for work - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With the MP3 player this problem will not have, because even the worst ones can last at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a charge.
Another problem happens when recording music on your cell phone.
Unfortunately, only a part of the devices has the universal USB connector and, moreover, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course it is possible to record music directly onto the memory card but only on some un-reduced readers can the small memory cards used in mobile phones be connected.
In the case of players, with some exceptions (iPod), no special software is required.
Just fill the device with music through the computer's USB.
Most mobile phones and players create their own order in the music library based on the name of the performer, album title, genre or also according to the user rating.
Some devices only display a directory with a tree structure similar to a Windows Finder and some recognize both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows more
The choice of equipment depends on the battery's strength, memory capacity, sound output quality and type and, of course, the comfort of use.
If you listen, above all, to music as a background and you listen to it every day for just a little while, like on the tram, then you can just have any mobile phone that plays it.
Which is practically what any mobile phone can do.
You should not even care about the format in which the mobile phone or the player plays the music.
MP3 is played by everyone and, practically, almost all music that comes to you will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and except for it the absolute majority of the devices play music in WMA format.
The least include the AAC format (format used by the company Apple and its iPod).
The best mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough to visit the relevant websites of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or an album.
This service alone could be a strong argument for purchasing a mobile for music.
Unfortunately, the operators' offer is miserable and most are limited only to the issues of fleeting radio success.
The prices are not the lowest either.
However, in general, it is assumed that this very way of selling music (whether via GSM, the internet or the wireless internet) will in the future dominate the music industry.
Most people always carry a cell phone with them.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you'll find your cell phone in your pocket, while your MP3 player will be left at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or, at least, handsfree ones.
If not, you can use an integrated player that has virtually every mobile phone even if it is at least an MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many of the music-enabled phones is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three grand.
Between three and four thousand crowns you can already buy a good walkman.
Most of you will be limited by the absence of a classic headphone jack.
The best ones, even in terms of the technical part, such as phones equipped with a 3.5 mm input for a classic headset, cost up to 15,000.
Again, the advantage of the players is nothing less than their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are really handled by anyone.
The minimal functions, its handling similar to previous ordinary cassettes or also to the turntables is obvious.
It does not pose a threat in the sense that we accidentally connect to the Internet with our mobile phone and, consequently, a huge data download bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for changing the memory card (M2 type, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card it will reach two thousand crowns.
Be careful, though.
Basic models are usually equipped with only a 2 GB maximum capacity card.
Only the most expensive ones have 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a cell phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, check out Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB), no more than 1.100 kroner is required.
If you are considered one of the most demanding music lovers, use the most specialized mobile walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of a single player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman line phones have almost identical use as an independent MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, over four thousand crowns, but with a greater memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and accumulator (usually 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the brand mentioned more arria brings them MP3 players.
The first virtual operator will be coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all the services of their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It'll probably be here soon.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the whole Union.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of roaming charges are likely to lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper than from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared with Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, has already said that there is no longer room in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a conventional operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find any frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market led to a significant price decline, which also affected traditional operators.
At the same time, even before the arrival of sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the British market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It showed that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, there is no need to look too far for examples.
In February this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from this, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, to operate effectively, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They do not entail relatively large costs in building, operating and maintaining the network.
In the world these types of virtual operators are usually characterized by low costs - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages which, however, are often counterbalanced by the offer of more tailored services.
For example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a not-so-trivial target group can also be a good hit.
This operator is specifically targeting the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it's the operator he likes and can trust", says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a concept like that of Poland could catch on in our country.
The Commission notes that the Czech Republic has not provided any evidence that the measure was necessary to achieve the objective of common interest.
In addition, from the point of view of the supply of services, it is relatively saturated.
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is to be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too promising.
Rather it is about the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region", Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, told mobil.cz in a telephone conversation.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible to prevent any potential competition from arising.
Interest in launching a virtual mobile operator is already being shown by the GTS Novera group, which wants to take a step forward to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of enterprise customers.
"We are very interested in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telephony services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators with this possibility.
With some of them we have managed to move forward in the meetings", said the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe better times are flashing.
It seems that, according to unofficial information, the first official operator should arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now, his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
'At the moment we believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator on the Czech market.
The Czech market is a very specific market compared to others.
Until now no one has approached us with any complex and serious project in this field", Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefonica O2, told mobil.cz.
The specific nature of the Czech market is also mentioned by other operators.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional agreement with O2, adds: 'To date we have not recorded any viable commercial project that, mutually beneficial, can continue to develop.'
He adds: "It will be difficult to find a virtual operator on the T-Mobile network until the end of the year.
We should already have on the table some concrete contract that could be studied in such a short timeframe".
Vodafone focuses its attention on the fulfilment of the requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický adds: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this concerns the sharing of costs and infrastructure.
We consider it precisely the greatest contribution from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to establish a shared network with a partner for fast mobile internet".
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators is easy to understand, but the entry of another operator would mean increased competition which would lead to lower prices and thus to lower profits.
So why facilitate entry into the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull on the same string, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on the ČTU was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is evidenced by the public information available on the ČTU's websites.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: 'Furthermore, the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was recently opened up to a fourth operator.
As regards the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would impose high demands on it and, above all, on its services.'
This is why this access to mobile operators is extremely discouraging because of the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the CTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This is purely the responsibility of the Office for the Protection of Trade Bids (OPCW).
However, the Commission expressed its typical position on this issue.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after an agreement on the lease of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator has been concluded.
To date no agreement has been concluded as the offer of potential interested parties was not interesting enough for the traditional operators", added Kristián Chalupa, from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
These statements do not surprise the operators' representatives.
For the offices which must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, and they must also ensure that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the foreign countries where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the fall in mobile phone prices"
The pressure to ensure that the market conditions are correct and that prices are lowered is obviously not in the interest of the ÚOHS.
What is really dramatically shocking about this whole case is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether this is really a coincidence, it offers itself.
It is the same as with the price of petrol at petrol stations, because it is clearly the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
'The Office has found no evidence of unfair competition in this respect and therefore has no grounds for any intervention.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore they do not have a corresponding increase in responsibility for their market behaviour.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as well as telecommunications regulators", added Chalupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of contention.
There is obviously an analysis of relevant markets by ČTÚ that telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of commercial tendering.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer a different view - for a virtual operator to emerge, agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
It must therefore be dominant in a particular segment.
And if this argument were not accepted, at least for ÚOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators are moving up in strikingly similar fashion.
The current complaints from interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with operators they encounter many similar impediments.
Charging the CTU with responsibility is a fairly common trick in the telecommunications field from which the ÚOHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We've met him before in a few similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act to extend the competence of the ČTU in the field of commercial tenders was recently introduced, but it did not come into effect, even though a number of experts promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of the OHIM must know this perfectly well, but their interests are clearly elsewhere.
Everything's fine, when no one's looking
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator is still operating unnoticed, which already exists in a few Czech mobile phone networks.
They are companies that set their own prices for mobile telephone services, but only a part of them are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a select few get the price list from these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer, you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this kind of resale.
"If cases like the one you mention were discovered, it could be said that the contractual conditions were breached and that this could result in the end of the partnership with the company", Martina Kemrová said when asked about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity by mobile phone operators would not reach responsible people.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, it may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
The activities of these companies generate not insignificant profits and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the potential problems: "The law allows for this type of speculation, yet the services of this company are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card of their phone is not in their name and therefore they cannot have it at their disposal as a normal customer of the operators".
This is precisely what should seem to the CTU minimally strange.
A new question for the OHCHR also appears.
If mobile operators are eyeing this kind of procedure, why are they blocking the virtual operator's entry?
It is necessary to add that the ÚOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it does not want to it should not be satisfied with the operators' explanations that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As already stated in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market led to a significant decrease in the prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where the virtual operator emerged, the conventional operators tried to more or less protect themselves from this breakthrough.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, possibly too saturated, problems with quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have now intervened and in no case have they defended the operators but their customers.
Whether it was with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to bring out the first virtual operator and with him began to emerge others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulator is passing this whole case by like a burning nail.
We cannot help but be impressed by our experience that the confusion of powers in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market will probably start moving again.
If any of the operators allows any virtual mobile operator to enter, it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech national anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four performances of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the Czech official celebrations day presented the new official recording of the anthem Where is my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one with male voice and one with female voice, one with Choir and one instrumental.
The singing is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the arrangements of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
The four versions can be heard on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national anthem one of the most beautiful.
Czech Radio has said before that it intentionally chose for the Solos singers with representatively young voices who are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried with both and then, also, with the Choir to look at the diction so that the text was well understood, so that it had consonance", he commented.
The Czech national anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home was first played in 1834 on the stages of the Theater of the States in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged to music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people embraced it.
The first stanza of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in the year 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
