The MHD in Prague brings us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers entered the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
It can be purchased at this moment by almost a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously load it onto their chip card at the transport company's information centres and stations at the Metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The bonds can be purchased online from yesterday on the transport company's website, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about the ticket booths in the metro stations, where until now they had to regularly queue to get a normal ticket.
The voucher is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged at one of the 13 branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is a window available to passengers with trained staff who help those interested with the purchase on the internet and also with the recharging of the voucher purchased on their card", said the spokesman for the project, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to top up the electronic voucher in the Opencard at vending machines in some subway halls.
What are these vending machines like?
They are red, reminiscent of a ticket machine, and travellers may have already noticed them at the metro stations of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Now there are five in the city but by the end of the year there should be eighty", Opatrný added.
The bond is controlled by the machine instead of the driver.
The operation of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Simply insert the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid bonus will be charged only on it.
The electronic vouchers from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, on the ring-trains and bus lines from numbers 300 to 499 used mainly by the inhabitants of the central Bohemian towns.
"On trains in Prague integrated transport there are checkers equipped with a reader card that will help confirm the validity of the time and zone of the ticket", explained ticket controller Filip Drápal of the organisation Ropid which sets the timetables for Prague public transport.
Circular buses have their reader cards mounted in the driver's compartment.
When entering the car, you must not only show the card to the driver but also accompany him with the Opencard in the designated place on the side of the box.
The driver then controls the validity of the voucher.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonuses there is nothing easier than to request the driver this information", Drápal added.
Passengers who do not travel on the ring-route buses and do not remember when their voucher expires can go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown information about the validity of your document.
The Southeasterners wanted to be part of the United States in a referendum.
The German Sudetenland asked in 1945 that Fumaba be part of the United States.
This is what is extracted from the letter which is kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
This is the wish that some Sudeten German groups allegedly addressed to the President of the United States in 1945.
It is the result of letters kept in a private archive and which are now kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Český Krumlov ask in a letter to the American president not to allow the return of the "Šumava land" - occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Pact - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and we really want your word that the American units are arriving on German soil not as oppressors or enemies but as liberators", the letter reads, signed with a "people who carry the fate of Šumava in their hearts".
Since the union of Czechoslovakia with the southeastern Germans presumably means - according to them - that the Czech national character is a hope only for brutality, recklessness, incomprehension, pressure and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take Šumava under a protectorate for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that without considering the opinion of four million inhabitants, we will be handed over to a foreign state that oppresses and rejects minorities and that in no way collaborates with the victory of the Allies", the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is presumably fear of reprisals from the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president were presumably to doubt this idea of the Šumavas, it would be enough to organise a referendum in the Šumavas lands on whether their inhabitants want to be part of the US or live under its patronage.
Although the letter's text may sound childish, some experts say it aptly portrays the expectations of Germans in the southeast at the time.
Although the Czech Germans must have had a slight sense that they were about to be expelled from the republic, only a few admitted this possibility.
Some hoped that the United States and Britain would negotiate for the Sudetenland some clear form of autonomy.
Others thought they would stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is confirmed even by the Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
He was in the war, as a German from Budějovice, enlisted in the Baltic navy.
When he was captured by the British at the end of the war and placed in the Holstein prison camp, dozens of Germans came to him to learn Czech.
"They thought that when they came home, the Czech would be good for them", Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, according to him, expected that on the basis of the Benevolent Decrees they would be removed from the Republic.
