Hidden by the expansive theme park of the greater Orlando, just a few miles from the glittering, noisy, colossal city, lies a quiet town, where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are very evident.
Eatonville, the first entirely black incorporated city in the country and the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 colored men, 300 good swimmers, many guayabas, two schools and not a jail".
It's a pilgrimage site now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! fair in Eatonville to pay tribute to Mrs. Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, in many ways, the city she described - also making it a tourist stopover by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Federal Writers Project of the depression season - remains a place apart.
The city remains independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Mrs. Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their true ideas with the white man, who "knows so little about us and who does not know what he is missing".
Even now, in the year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, has drawn attention to start a dialogue on the issue of race, many remain wary of the outsider.
"We're very cautious about how our story is told", said Jones Hortense, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city's oldest church.
"It has to be right".
Eatonville has always been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is at the same time a historic model of black affirmation and a community of nearly 2,400 people living below a poverty level twice the national average.
It's a literary center, but also a repaired example of the rural black Southern culture -- sometimes despised, sometimes praised -- that was born of slavery in America.
No wonder, if the residents here are both proud and reserved.
And the concern for Eatonville's image really started with Zora, as no one here calls her Mrs Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through her profound dialect books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a highway that runs through central Florida often forgotten inward black history and human drama.
Having a concrete face in both life and literature, Mrs. Hurston took her readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then into more private areas.
"Outside the road on the left", he wrote, "is the modern brown public school with its white finishes, its well-kept gardens and playgrounds, tended by Howard Miller, as he can barely read and write".
She also mentions the new husband of the widow Dash and writes that Glenn Lee "sells drinks of all kinds and anything goes with transitional rooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Mrs Hurston relates Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Obviously, this Fodor didn't.
In fact, not everyone appreciated the portrait.
"Zora described him as he was", said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls that Mrs. Hurston immortalized, quoting men who were singing colorless songs about their beauty.
He added: "Some people didn't like that".
Mrs. Hurston is still remembered here as a vivacious eccentric who returned frequently after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Franklin Augusto, 77, remembers that when Mrs. Hurston arrived in town, she did so without warning in a large Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still prides itself on dressing with dignity.
Most residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin said, while many laughed sarcastically.
"People were always very happy to see Zora", continues Mr. Franklin.
But, he adds, rocking in her chair in a backyard overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Mrs. Hurston was likely baptized, "she never stayed too long".
When Mrs. Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Like most of the world, Eatonville also seemed to have forgotten about her.
Although she was a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only woman of color at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce - Florida, where she had been living.
In Eatonville, there were no great memorial ceremonies, no great public readings.
"I don't think her contribution to the world or her legacy was understood", said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography of Mrs Hurston published in 2003.
A certain turn came in the 80s.
Orange County officials wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the working community's main two-lane street.
The expansion of the Orlando area had already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to his relatively idyllic isolation from the community.
In the '50s, the struggle for racial mix brought hatred about the community.
"During that season, a group of white boys, they would go around town throwing oranges and everything at the people who were sitting next to them", said Mr. Franklin.
"They also killed a girl once.
He was thrown into a watermelon from the car".
In a 1955 letter to Mrs. Hurston she wrote to The Orlando Sentinel, criticizing the forced integration by the Supreme Court that, in Brown v. Board of Education, "insulted rather than honored my race".
Residents say today that the desegregation of schools, positive in some respects, had weakened the cohesion of Eatonville and undermined the confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember this  it was used to hug the teacher in the morning and in the evening", said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit organization.
This lasted, he added, until teachers and students did not come from the same place.
"I wasn't hugging your teacher because he was white - there's a cultural gap there", said Mrs. Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped create space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons  black writers, actors and artists who went above and beyond prejudice, just as she did, with buzzing, confident lines like, "How can anyone deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I don't understand you".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker went to Mrs. Hurston's anonymous grave and began fighting to resurrect her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Mrs. Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway appeared in bookstores, reintroducing her into the American canon.
The road project came just as Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the spotlight.
And this time, Mrs. Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
In 1988, the community started planning a fair for Mrs. Hurston to show what the county could ruin with that road.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the celebration.
After several years, the county has abandoned its proposed road.
