No heels or flyers or opening costumes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of concentration on performance to obtain the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
The artist aside.
The other, the person.
Separate except in intimacy, in those moments of being out of the public eye, when you find the privacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of a hand, carefree because they're not going to come on stage.
German Günther Bauer alternates in "Flamenco-people" the theatricality of some stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with that lesser known side of these masters.
With this proposal, the photographer collects the particular iconography of flamenco from different areas.
Included in the program of the Month of Flamenco Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, growing every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco-people" "can be any people but, when looking at the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists on stage.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy... captivating the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, you don't have to take pictures of the stage.
They carry their personality and character inside.
My interest was to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with the camera the personality of the great flamenco players".
With the flavor of the festival "Cante de las Minas", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to portray the singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, due to the choice of camera and material, are reminiscent of classical photography.
The application of different stylistic media breaks with the classic basis of the image, giving it modernity, an idea that reflects how Bauer himself understands flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots, which evolves and surprises every day".
It is not the act of dancing, singing or touching itself, but the artist's personality, his character, that captivates the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential, with the leprechaun who makes himself visible in a way of feeling, being and being are and have been the constant of this work that is presented these days in the gallery El Fotómata.
Famous figures of the flamenco such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, make up this selection of almost seventy photographed artists.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited in the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "I love to portray people, meet them and be able to enter an instant in their life, be it a long or short moment.
I think that within photography, portraiture is the most difficult genre.
You meet or confront people, characters, who sometimes you don't even know, or who only give you a few minutes to take the photo.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true".
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people", is on display at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at number 20 de la Mata Street, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, where it can be visited until October 16.
