Talking in your sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up very awake telling us something about the day before, but children who talk in their sleep.
The first time it happens, you might get a little scared, but it doesn't really matter.
It's a benign sleep disorder called somniloquy.
It's quite common, especially in children and teenagers.
I'm sure more than one of you have heard that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime for example associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month, etc.), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its occurrence.
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime enuresis (peeping in your sleep) or sleepwalking, but this need not be the case.
As mentioned above, they may also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitation.
It's a little-studied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it appears is also highly variable.
He may speak in a calm tone of voice, with loose words, a murmur, or the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches, etc.).
In cases where the symptoms are very severe, it is advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if there is something that is causing the child to become very anxious.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stressful picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children who find it very difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a measure of inner calm.
This will help the child to sleep more soundly.
Once the sleepiness starts, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that happened.
Useful Tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not conscious, and you'll break his sleep.
Even though he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember, if you are very anxious during several episodes, you may want to check to see what is causing the child's anxiety.
If you can understand what he says (which is not usually the case), do not be tempted to interrogate him to get information.
You won't get anything, because he's asleep and he's not conscious enough to organize his thoughts.
Also, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, so be very careful how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to learn his secrets.
Not even for fun.
That creates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
