The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And most of all, he regained the public's trust that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, national blood banks managed by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated with Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In the face of this tragedy and public discontent, the Canadian government conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, presided over by Judge Horacio Krever, to clarify the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent it from happening again.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his report, certain provinces then set up a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been set up in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, almost 38 per cent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec", recalls Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
After having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and much work over the years that followed, we have regained the public's trust", he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, reminds us that "trust is extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were seeing the emergence in Europe of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We therefore rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious illness may result from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by brain degeneration which inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999 we refused blood to people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But some years ago it was shown beyond a doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle applied made sense".
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that directly detect the presence of the virus in the blood of donors rather than antibodies against the virus, which were the basis of previous tests.
Nucleic acid tests shortened the time between the time when the person was infected and the time when the first viruses could be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
We can reduce the risk of certain donors being infected without us knowing and not being able to detect them.
These improvements have greatly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-tainted blood.
"That means 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
So since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I believe that today you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to get back to health without worry", says Héma-Québec's chief executive.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
You never know what pathogen might emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant", says Dr Décary, before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for sufficient supply.
"Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Because more aggressive cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which represents on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate blood. "
All healthy persons 18 years of age and above who meet the eligibility criteria may, however, donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is prevalent, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
Hardship is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can't donate their blood anymore.
But it's hard to convince people to donate their blood, but it's hard to keep them and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since life is so unbridled today, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood", laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was once considered biomedical waste, is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases like leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, the placement in the bank of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample and are expected to take more than a thousand of these per year.
We should start proposing it for grafts early next year", says Dr. Décary who describes this cord blood program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed not to be able to enjoy this", since Héma-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
