Free opinion - The Orwellian discourse of Barrick Gold
In its issue of 17 September, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr Patrick J. Garver, vice-president and director of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the world's largest gold company filed a six million euro defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of persecution for libel, but the law.
Not surprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to harm anyone who dares to take a position contrary to his own?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little importance, the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will muzzle the opposition as well as scare anyone who dares to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it is before the public that it would have had to present its view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, debates in Canada are normally done by changing ideas and not by baton blows.
It was enough for the mining company to open its books, its files and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent research teams that could have clarified the matter.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and rejects the petitions and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr Garver possibly explain how he can ask for a "public" debate and disregard his views?
According to the Vice-President, it seems that this word refers only to high-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In a democracy, critics also have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada does so mainly because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but on the basis of civilized changes of argument, and not in the context of what many people perceive as a persecution-bite (pursuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a request with respect to the authors of Noir Canada instructing them not to use this word anymore).
In addition to Mr Garver's surreal speech, the Barrick Gold trial is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and truth, which are essential for all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the rich corporations of this world in a country like Canada, under pain of much persecution, who can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right to an objection.
The academic world, to which we belong, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
The excessive persecution of Barrick Gold clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, but also for public debate in Canada, and it is high time that governments put in place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
