What was produced at the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory?
The criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will be opened very soon, on 8 October.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing fraud of significant damage, as a business, continuously and in an organized manner in addition to other crimes, among them the falsification of documents.
According to the Prosecutor's Office, they used the funds obtained in public tenders for their own purposes, justifying the fulfillment of the tasks with false invoices.
The public and municipal funds - some HUF 65 million in all - went partly into the treasury of the Fiatal Baloldal organisation and partly into the pockets of private individuals.
The method, which was also made known by the researchers, was to justify the collection of funds obtained in public tenders with false invoices behind which there was no actual execution, the various associations never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the prosecution, most of the invoices were fake.
For this they obtained the stamps from the market in Józsefváros District and the circular stamps were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question of which company to make the counterfeit invoice was decided among others in that tour of the Upper Balaton Region where János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for a bill for his consumption and these served as a model for making the bills that he presented among others in the competitions of the Ministry of Youth Affairs and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor, as well as the City Council of the Capital.
These bills were signed mostly by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who according to our information rather wrote the reports necessary to obtain the public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" Lados chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this food centre provided food for a group of 90 people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However, according to the manager of the center, not all the people can fit in at once.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation - later called Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
For one hostel in Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and no more than ten people could stay there in one night, yet the bill was for one hundred and thirty people.
But the manufacturers of large fantasy invoices also exaggerated when they pointed to the Pigal Kft. food centre because in the bookshop of the same - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the manager of the company, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned by the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he already knew that they were fake documents.
"On the stamp, our company name and ID number were in the wrong place".
He added: besides the formal problems, he also did not agree that according to the bill 100 people were accommodated, since they have only eleven rooms that do not fit so many people.
In addition, the bill included meals, while the restaurant has not been operating for a long time.
The enthusiastic invoicers were also not informed that the travel agency chosen in Budapest organised only international trips, so that on the cash payment invoice they foolishly indicated a journey within Hungary as a service, which also did not coincide with the agency's invoicing practice.
In addition, as was found out during the investigation, VAT was also included in the document, even though travel outside the territory of the European Union was exempt from tax.
Among other things, the VAT measure was also incorrect in the four documents issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the services of this company are not charged with 25 but only 15 per cent VAT, and the hotel employees only issued machine-made invoices but the invoice was manual.
In addition, the "expeditor" made other mistakes as well, such as in the case of a company in which they put in the invoice as activity carried out the transport by road which - it became known during the investigations of the prosecutor's office - does not perform the company founded as a consultant of investments.
Also due to formal differences - inadequate form of the invoice, false stamp - it became known that the invoices issued for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont were false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehertó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued those invoices.
The counterfeiters also failed to notice that when the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation, so the liquidation process manager - according to our information - denied having issued such a document.
They knowingly issued the invoices
Another group of counterfeit invoice makers are those who were aware that they were supposed to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, issued an invoice worth about HUF four million in the name of the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért.
The manager of Collab Kft. - according to the indictment - was convinced by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue fictitious invoices.
Biogate Kft., which is currently in liquidation, also cooperated with Zuschlag and its accomplices and in 2003 supplied invoices worth approximately HUF 5 million to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, without any real economic activity behind them.
There was no capital movement either, because after they canceled the bills prepared but forgot to include this entity in their documents.
The next group of counterfeit invoice makers include those who have some connection to the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was the plaintiff of the Ukrainian manager of the fictitious Delta Trio SL based in Budapest, which was engaged in the trade of fuels and vehicles.
This company issued numerous invoices for the sale of computer media worth approximately HUF 18 million in October, November and December 2005.
According to the investigation data, these invoices were purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The manager of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov should have also sent the documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
We have information that Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he issued invoices for the company's Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and collected the amount himself.
Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
However, none of the companies actually worked because - according to the defendant - they were not given work.
But he benefited from these companies, since at the request of his accomplice, the lawyer Zsolt Szente, who prepared the company registration documents, they issued invoices in the name of the companies for the organizations linked to Zuschlag: for the Atlasz and for the Y-Generáció.
Kubatov on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trio, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade issued a total of 15 invoices to different entities for a value of HUF 14,2 million.
The prosecutor's office found that Kubatov received VAT and 10% of the invoice amount.
That man even took advantage of the Szi-Beri limited partnership to issue fictitious invoices used in the Biztos Pont contest.
The Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted a competition in January 2006 to Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA), a public utility of the Socialist Party.
They obtained HUF 500 000 respectively from the competition, but did not use the money for the competition's objectives.
To avoid this being discovered, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft were presented to the TMA.
These were the bills found during the registration of the office that Árpád Kemecsei had at the headquarters of the Ministry of Education.
Some of the accused will probably tell at trial - as they did at the Prosecutor's Office - the course of the counterfeiting of the invoices.
The most interesting thing may be the confession of the main defendant János Zuschlag himself, if he decides to dismantle everything.
Well, his confessions so far have not been very detailed and although he has repeatedly promised to talk about everything, this has not been done until now.
The question is: what interest does he have in doing so? Perhaps in return for the return of most of the money - HUF 50 million - the Socialists have reached an agreement with him that Zusi will take on all the responsibility.
Who, on the other hand, for these days even could be offended, since to ease his prison conditions he requested house arrest, but was repeatedly denied.
While the numerous perpetrators of far higher value economic crimes, who never returned the money, walk free or at least can wait in their own homes for sentence, he has no chance for that.
Overlapping psychology: Why are we spending more money?
Participants in auctions are prone to spending more money and overvaluing the product.
Neuroscientists and economists at New York University have discovered the neurological-economic basis for this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose out on competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, the other participated in an auction, and the active areas of the brain of the experimental participants were examined by functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, participants could win money, but during auctions, where betting more than the other is a fundamental element, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the nervous system's "self-reward" mechanism.
So according to scientists, the increase in gambling is explained as a prevention to avoid provoking an intense reaction of the stratum.
To support their theory, the economists of the scientific group also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 prize.
The third group, on the other hand, received exactly $15 before the auction, but if they lost the auction, the group members lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that one group was highlighted as a success and the other as a failure.
However, testing the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the "fail-safe" group were willing to gamble even more than the members of the control group and the "win" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
The Commission has not yet been able to provide any information on the results of the auctions.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation", said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University's Graduate School of Business.
Hepatitis: When should you see a doctor?
Worldwide, some half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is considered a leading cause of death in Hungary.
The number of infected in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 are being treated because many of the patients do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common name for several liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar - liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause are very different.
Hepatitis virus dependent on pathogen are spread by two main means: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with contaminated water or food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal humour, saliva).
It is recommended that travellers protect themselves by vaccination against A and B viruses, there are no vaccines against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating the infected food, and are manifested by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain, and nausea.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and whites of the eyes, the excrement becomes clear, the urine dark and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Each year, one million people worldwide die from cancer and cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of the disease.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people receive drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences. Without treatment, it can cause cirrhosis of the liver and even cancer.
Most people who are infected do not know they are sick because this pathogen gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms do not appear until 20 to 30 years later.
So early detection, systematic medical monitoring is very important.
The disease is much more common in three groups: people who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and tattoo wearers.
There are now about 200 million people worldwide who have chronic hepatitis C.
Since this disease can be detected with a routine laboratory check-up as well, it is worth consulting your family doctor if you experience any unknown symptoms.
The disease is curable if it is detected early, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus suppressing the infection and preventing cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
The aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic viral liver infections and the importance of early detection.
Does it hurt less for people who believe in God?
According to a recent study, religious faith has a calming effect that even alleviated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment to see how religious belief influences human grief, reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
In this unique experiment, they shocked 12 Catholics and an equal number of atheists while they were all looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, the Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Using the human brain scanning technique, it was verified that Catholic believers were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain regulation.
This experiment is the first in a series of research projects involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from the various departments of the University.
The analysis was as follows: a sparkling instrument was fixed to the patient's left hand, which was then electrocuted.
Researchers asked participants to fix their eyes on two paintings - the 17th-century Sassoferrato painting of the Virgin Mary and Leonardo da Vinci's 15th-century Lady of the Armour.
The researchers hoped that the Virgin Mary's spectacle would stir up a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a calming effect.
Patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in that period in four successive parts while looking at the painting of either the religious theme or the other.
Catholics claimed that looking at the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe" as "protected" persons, "reassured and peaceful in their hearts".
When they looked at the religious painting, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who was also involved in the experiment, thinks that with any image that shocks you can get a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find a portrait of a person they feel very positive about, like a mother or a father", said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases does change our personality", Wright added.
After these remarkable results, one question remains: What effect would it have on pain regulation if the Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of his size were shown to the faithful?
Would a high-quality vision of a Virgin Mary yield even better results?
You are what you say you are
On its tenth birthday, Google can claim: you can find it in people's pockets, as well as in the sky above their heads; you know where they spent their holidays, which doctors they visit and what they are interested in.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who draw parallels with the Orwellian vision do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect as much personal data as possible about its users, and this is necessary to be able to fulfill the original goals of the founders of Google: "we gather in one system all the information in the world!".
According to the Google leader, the company even after ten years of work that revolutionized the world is still in the early stages of the commitment to be able to process all information.
When asked what will happen in five years' time, Schmidt replied: "I wish Google could answer questions like 'What should I do tomorrow?' or 'What would be the best job for me?' - but software cannot answer seemingly simple questions unless there is enough information from users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their Internet browsing, the searched keywords, IP addresses and pages they went to when they finished the search are accurately stored.
For example, thanks to Personalized Search, which debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can revisit what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches - on this same logic will be based the Recommendations, in which the system will offer us products and services based on the preferences previously defined and stored.
What if they use my data against me, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who are worried about seeing Google's information monopoly.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what can be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, longing for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that not only do they keep, but in justifiable cases also cede to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most discussed example of recent times was perhaps the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google handed over the information from its website, called Orkut, to the Brazilian government to identify pedophiles.
Instead, Internet users who care about people's rights were relieved in May when the company along with the EFF, an organization for the defense of electronic rights, successfully proved in court that they were right in their litigation with the FBI: according to the ruling, Google cannot be forced, by any of the constitutional clauses, to provide any kind of information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time the federal government managed to get under the pretext of enforcing the child protection law passed years ago, about fifty thousand web addresses and about a thousand searched phrases, but without getting the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of web pages and keywords from the last two months.)
So the opinion about Google is quite contradictory: it is criticized by those who are afraid to provide their personal data because they think that their privacy, their privacy is harmed by starting to use Google services, and they rebel against it as against the conservative-looking multinational companies.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, netizens and users from other countries, see them as the next generation, the "avant-garde corporation", not their rival, Microsoft, who is labeled by its Windows as the conqueror of the world, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
This may be because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for their applications, the code is open and the free program package, constantly updated and looks more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks see precisely the very problematic relationship between human rights and the Internet that has been produced by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, about leaving intentional footprints behind us and taking advantage of the available communication channels, and while the measurements of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: showing ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even link them with other services, such as Twitter or last.fm that lists their music habits, then include them in a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also have a blog, in which the latest photo galleries that are stored on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
We can know of numerous cases where it is clear that for example the bride, by seeing the flow of photos of the next morning of common friends, finds out who her fraudulent boyfriend spent the night with the night before or they can fire an employee of a company because he writes his honest opinion on his blog about the management of the company: one thing is for sure, the definition of privacy has been completely revalued.
A person's online life is what he shows of himself - this is the definition that lies behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least wants to dodge Google's monopoly, can do so (starting with Scroogle, for example, which uses Google's search engine, but leaves no footprints).
There are many people who don't want to register on the social pages to avoid being found, but Google's online apps, from word processing software to image and news reading apps, can be replaced with alternative versions that don't connect to giant servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
The public is almost openly waiting for the day when Google shows its true face.
The company, with its current value of $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising surfaces threaten advertising agencies' revenues, while services that are being introduced more and more rapidly are causing serious headaches not only for Microsoft, but also for numerous other software companies.
Critical observers, however, will find the contradictions alarming as well: for example, top management flatly rejected the employees' protest after doubling the price of the company's daycare, deemed unlimited employee meals too expensive, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 Google gave in to Chinese government pressure and the company under the agreement leaked all information that violated the good morals and interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal regulations says that they will not announce any new service in advance, but only when it is ready to work, which is sure to be the predictable problems of the coming months and years that could rock the world: while some believe that Google's project of scanning and archiving books and magazines will take on such dimensions that the company will soon be cited by the Supreme Court of the United States, others fear its Health system, because in it we can create our own complete health profile, with previous analyses, with our doctors and our problems.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database, it may provide a good raw material for science fiction writers, Scroogled, the popular novel by Cory Doctorow, describes in an Orwellian way that future, in which a man just from Google data can be described alarmingly well.
