The intelligent car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What better way to develop technologies to avoid collisions than by mimicking obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, the bee.
In a startling project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the BR23C-type robotic steering system for cars mimicking nature, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, RP and R&D technology director at the exhibition.
The honeybee's compound eyes play an important role in this. They can see in all directions at an angle of over 300 degrees.
To mimic the function of compound eyes, engineers used the laser-beam length-measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 metres, at a 180-degree angle, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle's microprocessor which is immediately transformed into a collision avoidance maneuver.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle's robot, imitating the movements of the bumblebees, changes direction by turning the wheels as needed.
Unlike any system in existence today, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If this were not the case, the vehicle robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process must be done in a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels
So instead of the endless possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the car robot the rotary motion and acceleration plus the braking.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, let alone the storage capacity.
This device only has to process a few input signals every second and react as needed.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data from the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
You don't need gigabytes of memory, or megabytes.
This is the first step in developing technology to avoid obstacles immediately, which Nissan estimates will be available in series-produced models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, dodging obstacles in his path.
