Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008 domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to prices last month and by 12.9 percent compared to prices in August 2007 - the Central Statistics Office (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices increased by 1,1% compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3,9% compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose 0.7 percent from the previous month and 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only marginally by 0.1%.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors increased slightly, by 0.1 per cent compared with July.
The largest increase in price magnitude was in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2,8 per cent), mainly due to the 4,6% monthly increase in bags and belts and the 2,5% increase in footwear.
The higher price level of the basic materials plastics and chemicals resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical materials production branch (1,6%).
Price decreases were recorded in the petrochemical sector (1.4%), in the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0.9%) and - to a lesser extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1%).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry, prices rose by between 0.2 and 0.9%.
The supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which are an important part of domestic trade, increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly as a result of the increase in official prices from 1 July.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
The metalworking sector saw an increase of 13.2 percent, while the food, beverage and tobacco industries, which account for the bulk of the work, saw an increase of 11 percent.
Prices fell in the textile industry (2.5%) and in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3%).
In the other processors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1%.
Over the past year, prices in the global processing industry rose by 10.2 percent.
Prices for electricity, gas, heat and water were 18.7 percent higher than the previous year.
In August, the largest monthly price increase (0.7%) was recorded in the investment goods sector.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices rose by 0.3%, while prices in the energy and intermediate sectors were unchanged on the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increases were in the energy and intermediate industry sectors (16,8%).
The consumption goods industries declined by 6.8 per cent and the investment goods by 1.4 per cent.
The industry's export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in one month decreased by 1.7 percent against the euro and by 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
