Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
The European Summit on Equal Opportunities opened today in Paris, hosted by France, which is also holding the Presidency of the European Union this year.
Lívia Járóka, MEP for the European People's Party for Fidesz, in her message to the plenary, as one of the main speakers at this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that afflict gypsy children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevailing foundation of their interests.
The high-level conference was opened on behalf of the French Presidency by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, the European social partners and representatives of the main European organisations for the protection of social rights.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of MEPs in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to employment discrimination, Roma are excluded from the labour market primarily because of their low level of education.
"Most young Roma have not finished secondary school and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a negligible proportion can obtain a university diploma".
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investing in the early education of Roma children can strengthen the economies of the Member States of the European Union.
The Commission is also proposing to increase the number of EU-funded projects in the field of education and training.
The earlier a Gypsy student starts school, the more chances he has of becoming an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"The Roma, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to a quality education and the abolition of segregated and low-level education", stressed Lívia Járóka.
The Commission is also proposing to increase the number of EU citizens who are eligible for EU funding for education and training.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer gypsy children the possibility that guarantees the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens", he said.
The aim of the European Equal Opportunities Summit, which has been held annually since last year's Berlin meeting, which was held under the banner of the 'European Year for Equal Opportunities', is to provide a unique forum for promoting the elimination of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
