Listening to loud music for a long time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent damage to hearing.
This is the view of the European Commission, which in a statement published in Brussels quotes the opinion of the European Union's Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (CSERIS), published today.
"From this scientific opinion  it appears in the footnote  that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day with the device at high volume risk permanent hearing loss".
"I am concerned that such a high number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and cell phones at high sound levels may unknowingly ruin their ears beyond repair", says Meglena Kuneva.
'The scientific evidence  shows that the EU is responsible - a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
What matters is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion, so that they are broadly effective and keep pace with new technology.'
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to look into the problem, seeing the high use of portable music devices and the increasing number of young people exposed to the noise they cause.
'Scientists confirm that this is a cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine with Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical and related devices.'
There is already a European safety standard limiting the noise level of portable music devices to 100 dB, but concern is growing as hearing damage can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to greatly limit this damage by resorting to solutions such as reducing noise exposure levels and time.
The European Scientific Committee considers that users of portable music devices who listen to music at high volume (over 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceed the currently applicable limit for maximum permissible noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk permanent hearing loss after a period of 5 years.
This means that it affects 5-10% of users of such devices and the number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
