The possibility of harvesting energy from sea movements has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, together with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was shelved, but now environmental concerns and the new rise in oil give the sector a boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated that by 2007 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by implants that exploit the movement of the sea waves.
This would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power plants today.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build an implant in northern Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
"Chevron is studying technology on ocean energy", a spokesman for a company associated with the US oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us".
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the US Energy Commission to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It is a pretty important sign, considering that in Alaska the US continues to drill for oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to drill further.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are following the path of energy that comes from the sea, the total invested so far, although not detailed, indicate an increasing interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts talk about a technology still in its infancy, because marine energy has no doubt a great environmental impact.
For now, impacts such as those of the Portuguese or the Scots are small and do not seem to cause major problems to the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, a technology with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the options are many: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boas connected to each other.
The force of the waves, which moves the boa up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside the boa.
The pressure makes a turbine spin, which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to the coast through underwater cables.
There are four such implants currently in development, pending federal approval, some of which could be used for a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot, using underwater turbines on the East River in New York.
The movement of water when there's a tide, it turns the turbine's blades, creating a rotational motion that powers the generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permits to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Particular interest, say the Institute for Electrical Energy Development, is now due to the potential of tides.
Although intermittent, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It's mostly about tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others that are near the coast, have invested $7.5 million in 2008 and are planning a $35 million investment by 2009.
